     <p><strong><p><strong>Amie L. Thomasson, <em>Rethinking Metaphysics</em>, Oxford University Press, 2025, 280pp., $35.00 (hbk) ISBN 9780197787809.</strong></p></strong></p>
     <p><strong>Reviewed by Timothy Williamson, Oxford University</strong></p>
     <p>Amie Thomasson is a leader of a programme for deflating the pretensions of metaphysics and finding something better for philosophers to do. She locates this programme within a broad neo-pragmatist tradition. Her latest book is a further contribution to the overall project and updates it by reference to recent trends in metaphysics.</p> <p>The first half of the book tries to show that there are no deep metaphysical truths out there to be discovered. This enterprise risks self-defeat, for if there are no deep metaphysical truths out there, that itself looks suspiciously like a deep metaphysical truth discovered by Thomasson and her allies, if their arguments work.</p> <p>Thomasson starts by emphasizing the lack of agreement in contemporary metaphysics, and the dim prospects for achieving it. This...
